description.plain:
On “Old Town Road,” Lil Nas X romanticizes the life of a cowboy. The character is unfulfilled by a hedonistic life of consumerism, substance abuse, and adultery. He also has dissatisfaction with the indolence of his peers, feeling no need to heed their advice. With nothing left to believe in or follow, the rider heads out with the only destination being the open road.

“Old Town Road” grew in popularity through numerous TikTok memes. Similarly to how the Atlanta duo iLOVEFRiDAY’s hit song “Mia Khalifa” blew up, clips on TikTok with the hashtag #oldtownroad have garnered millions of views.

After the song was removed from Billboard’s Country charts for “not (embracing) enough elements of today’s country music to chart in its current version,” Lil Nas X released a remix of his song with Billy Ray Cyrus to spite the company. The original eventually reached the number 1 spot on the Billboard Hot 100 on April 8, 2019.

Both the original version and the remix credits Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross of Nine Inch Nails for sampling their track, “34 Ghosts IV.”

description.plain:
“Panini” is the second single from Lil Nas X’s debut EP, 7, following his hit song, “Old Town Road.” It was first previewed on his Instagram on April 2nd, 2019, with the caption, “Sayyyyyy tooo meee.”

In this song, Lil Nas talks about his old fanbase and compares them to Panini, a character from the popular TV Series Chowder.

Nas explained what he meant by the song in a Genius suggestion:

Panini was possessive over Chowder in the show. She’s a representation of fans of who love you when you’re small. Once you get the spotlight they aren’t feeling you as much. The song is not a diss but anger towards that fan but also wanting them back.

On May 12, 2019, Lil Nas premiered the song in its entirety for the first time at the Rolling Loud music festival. It features production credit from Dot Da Genius and the producing duo Take A Daytrip.

“C7osure (You Like)” finds Nas telling someone he loves (maybe, his fans or his family) that he needs to grow, and that fear or worry won’t hold him back: a similar theme is present on “Panini,” a more direct “letter” to those who have been disappointed by his rapid rise to fame.

The song was first teased on the 7th of June, 2 weeks before the release of the project.

“Kick It” is the 4th track on Lil Nas X’s debut EP, 7. The track is told by the perspective of a fake friend. In fact, the person speaking in the song has heard about Lil Nas X’s new found success and is trying to act like he/she was there with Nas from the start: as he doesn’t care about him/her, he/she becomes an hater by throwing dirt on his name, his talent and his credibility as an artist.

It was originally previewed on May 2nd on his Instagram with the caption, “WHAT’S Y'ALL TOP 3 SNIPPETS NOW?!”.

description.plain:
5 months before Lil Nas X’s track, “Old Town Road,” the viral rapper uploaded “CARRY ON” to YouTube and Soundcloud. The track explains his distress in his environment, which is a contrast to his hit “Old Town Road,” a song that sounds like it is expressing more freedom. You can also think of the track as a precursor to his #1 single, since CARRY ON’s lyrical content shows the distress he of his environment, which contrasts to “Old Town Road,” a song that represents freedom and letting go of his fears.

The track is produced by Wynter, who originally uploaded a “Pierre Bourne x Playboi Carti Type Beat” on YouTube in early 2018. The beat samples Bobby Caldwell’s “Carry On” (1982), which was also sampled by Madlib on M.E.D.’s (aka Medaphor) “Can’t Hold On” (2005). However, neglect to clear it provoked a 25 million dollar lawsuit against Lil Nas X, producer Wynter, and Sony by The Music Force, claiming he and the producer were “motivated by greed and malicious intent”.

description.plain:
“Sonic Shit” is a song by Lil Nas X originally released on Soundcloud on 8 June 2018. After his overwhelming break-out success with “Old Town Road” and its subsequent remix with Billy Ray Cyrus, Lil Nas X re-released “Sonic Shit” as a single for his debut album on 10 April 2019.

While the lyrics remained constant between the two iterations, the most notable change was its cover art, which changed from a picture of Sonic the Hedgehog to a picture of himself in a camo hoodie.

The song released amidst tensions of fans expecting “Titanic” to be the follow-up release to “Old Town Road.”

description.plain:
“Don’t Want It” is an upcoming song from Atlanta rapper Lil Nas X.

It features producer credits from Nick Mira and Lil Nas X himself, as this is the first song he’s helped co-produce on.

The song interpolates the folk nursery rhyme “Hush, Little Baby” in its chorus. Lil Nas X isn’t the first rapper to do so—the song was also sampled in Eminem’s “Mockingbird”.

Lil Nas X first previewed the song on Twitter on April 3, 2019. The song is expected to be released on Lil Nas X’s debut album Project X.

description.plain:
“Titanic” was expected to be Lil Nas X’s second single of off his upcoming project and his first release since his worldwide hit “Old Town Road.”
The song was teased several times and sees the Atlanta artist reflecting on how money satisfies a women, but also prevents him from getting too involved in this relationship.

The title of the song refers to the Titanic, the mythic British passenger liner that sank in the North Atlantic Ocean after colliding with an iceberg in 1912. Lil Nas X draws a parallel between the state of his relationship and the shipwreck of the famous vessel.

On the 12th of April, Lil Nas X hinted at an imminent release. However, he later announced that the release of the song was pushed back due to “technical difficulties.”

Lil Nas X later teased the song again on October 18, 2019, with a beat that had seemingly been changed.

description.plain:
Montero Lamar Hill (born April 9th, 1999), better known by his stage name Lil Nas X, is a hip-hop artist from Atlanta. He dropped out of his freshman year in college in 2018 to pursue music full time. Regarding this, he said:

Everybody thought I was crazy, I knew what I was doing. Thank you everyone, this just the mf beginning!

On July 24th, 2018, he released his debut mixtape titled NASARATI.

On December 2nd, 2018, he released the hit “Old Town Road” which blew up through TikTok memes. It finally entered the Billboard Hot 100 in early March 2019. Old Town Road reached #1 on Spotify, iTunes and Apple Music as well as becoming the first song to simultaneously chart on the Billboard country and hip-hop/R&B charts before it was disqualified from the country charts. This caused lots of controversies. The track was eventually remixed featuring country singer Billy Ray Cyrus.

On April 3rd, 2019, it was revealed on Michael McCrudden’s popular YouTube show, “Before They Were Famous,” how Lil Nas X got his rap name. He said:

It was originally Lil Nas just to be ironic ‘cause every new rapper’s name has 'lil.’ Kinda got stuck with ‘lil’ after building a small fanbase.
Added the ‘X’ later on standing for the amount of years until I feel like I will be considered a legend.

On May 13, 2019, Billboard confirmed Lil Nas X signed with CAA for worldwide representation.

On June 21, 2019, Lil Nas released his debut EP, 7.
